data.content:
Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`. Both work as expected:

```csharp
Span<nint> nints = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system, each `nint`/`nuint` element is 8 bytes. On a 32-bit runtime they'd be 4 bytes. No special directives or unsafe context needed â€” `stackalloc` into a `Span<T>` is safe code.
